  "narrative_arc": "Escaped from slavery and killed her own daughter rather than let her be returned to bondage. Morrison documents the interior architecture of slavery's aftermath — not just the physical scars on Sethe's back (shaped like a tree) but the way memory itself becomes a haunting. The house at 124 is both shelter and prison.",
  "why_this_character_matters": "Sethe's dome maps trauma as a layer that sits on top of all others. Her Layer 10 (Autonomy) action — killing her child to free it — is the most extreme autonomy claim in this catalog. Building her dome reveals whether any system could have offered an alternative.",
